[[File:Embassytheatredayjex.jpg|250px|thumb|Left|The de Lux Theatre. Now known as the Embassy Theatre.]]
He represented the [[Wellington South (New Zealand electorate)|Wellington South]] electorate in Parliament from [[New Zealand general election, 1908|1908]] to [[New Zealand general election, 1911|1911]] when he was defeated, then the [[Wellington Suburbs and Country]] electorate from [[New Zealand general election, 1914|1914]] to 1919 and the [[Wellington Suburbs (New Zealand electorate)|Wellington Suburbs]] electorate from [[New Zealand general election, 1919|1919]] to [[New Zealand general election, 1938|1938]]. In the 1935 contest Wright stood as an [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] and was successful.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=247}} He was defeated for the [[Wellington West (New Zealand electorate)|Wellington West]] electorate in [[New Zealand general election, 1938|1938]].{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=247}} In 1935 and 1938 he was not opposed by the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]], and he habitually voted with National.<ref>{{cite book |first = Robert Stephen |last = Milne |title = Political Parties in New Zealand |place = [[Oxford]], England |publisher = [[Clarendon Press]] |year = 1966 |page = 76}}</ref>

Wright stood for and was elected Mayor of Wellington in 1921, the same time as Wellington's first female Councillor, [[Annie McVicar]], was elected. Wright was Mayor until 1925.<ref>http://www.wellington.govt.nz/services/history/mayors/1921.html</ref> On 31 October 1924 Wright opened the de Lux Theatre on the corner of Cambridge Terrace and Majoribanks Street. In 1930 the building was sold and renamed the [[Embassy Theatre, Wellington|Embassy Theatre]] and was the site of the premiere of [[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King#Release|Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]].<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/business/our-people/7339227/Cutting-edge-technology-in-historic-surroundings</ref>

He was [[Minister of Education (New Zealand)|Minister of Education]] from 1926 to 1928 in the [[Reform Government of New Zealand|Reform Government]]. Towards the end of the Coates Ministry, he was [[Minister of Labour (New Zealand)|Minister of Labour]] for less than a fortnight.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=79}}

He was to stand for the National Party for [[Wellington Suburbs (New Zealand electorate)|Wellington Suburbs]] in the 1941 general election, which was postponed because of the war.<ref>{{cite book |last = Gustafson |first = Barry |authorlink = Barry Gustafson |title = The First 50 Years : A History of the New Zealand National Party |year = 1986 |publisher = Reed Methuen |location = Auckland |isbn = 0-474-00177-6 |page = 295}}</ref>

A brother, [[Hercules Richard Wright]] was a notable Rugby League player.

